y]]{{refn|The Sparks traded this pick to Connecticut for [[Chiney Ogwumike]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wnba.com/news/sparks-acquire-2014-no-1-overall-pick-chiney-ogwumike/|title=Sparks Acquire 2014 No. 1 Overall Pick Chiney Ogwumike|website=wnba.com|publisher=WNBA|date=April 27, 2019|accessdate=April 27, 2019}}</ref>|group=lower-alpha|name=note_c}},{{refn|group=lower-alpha|name=note_i}}\n| \n|-\n| 11\n| \n| \n| [[Seattle Storm]]{{refn|group=lower-alpha|name=note_a}}\n| \n|-\n| 12\n| \n| \n| [[Washington Mystics]]\n| \n|}\n\n===Second round===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n|-\n! width=30|Pick\n! width=333|Player\n! width=200|Nationality\n! width=383|WNBA Team\n! width=333|School/Club Team/Country\n|-\n| 13\n| \n| \n| [[Atlanta Dream]]\n| \n|-\n| 14\n| \n| \n| [[Indiana Fever]]{{refn|The Liberty traded this pick to Minnesota for [[Tanisha Wright]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://liberty.wnba.com/news/liberty-acquires-guard-tanisha-wright-in-exchange-for-2020-second-round-pick/|title=Liberty Acquires Guard Tanisha Wright in Exchange for 2020 Second Round Pick|website=liberty.wnba.com|publisher=WNBA|date=April 11, 2019|accessdate=April 15, 2019}}</ref>|group=lower-alpha|name=note_d}},{{refn|The Lynx traded this pick and their 2021 second round pick to Indiana for [[Shenise Johnson]] and the 16th pick.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://fever.wnba.com/news/shenise-johnson-traded/|title=Fever Acquire Draft Picks in Trade with Minnesota|website=fever.wnba.com|publisher=WNBA|date=March 6, 2020|accessdate=March 10, 2020}}</ref>|group=lower-alpha|name=note_l}}\n| \n|-\n| 15\n| \n| \n| [[Dallas Wings]]{{refn|group=lower-alpha|name=note_b}}\n| \n|-\n| 16\n| \n| \n| [[Minnesota Lynx]]{{refn|group=lower-alpha|name=note_l}}\n| \n|-\n| 17\n| \n| \n| [[Atlanta Dream]]{{refn|As part of a three team deal, the Mercury traded this pick to Atlanta.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.espn.com/wnba/story/_/id/28737240/mercury-acquire-jessica-breland-3-team-deal-dream-sun|title=Mercury acquire Jessica Breland in 3-team deal with Dream, Sun|website=espn.com|publisher=ESPN|first=Josh|last=Weinfuss|date=February 19, 2020|accessdate=February 19, 2020}}</ref>|group=lower-alpha|name=note_k}}\n| \n|-\n| 18\n| \n| \n| [[Phoenix Mercury]]{{refn|The Lynx traded this pick to Phoenix for [[Stephanie Talbot]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://mercury.wnba.com/news/mercury-acquire-2020-second-round-pick-from-minnesota/|title=Mercury Acquire 2020 Second-Round Pick From Minnesota|website=wnba.com|publisher=WNBA|date=May 21, 2019|accessdate=May 21, 2019}}</ref>|group=lower-alpha|name=note_e}}\n| \n|-\n| 19\n| \n| \n| [[Seattle Storm]]\n| \n|-\n| 20\n| \n|\n| [[Los Angeles Sparks]]{{refn|The Sky traded this pick to Los Angeles for [[Jantel Lavender]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wnba.com/news/los-angeles-sparks-trade-jantel-lavender-to-chicago-sky/|title=Los Angeles Sparks Trade Jantel Lavender To Chicago Sky|website=wnba.com|publisher=WNBA|date=May 20, 2019|accessdate=May 20, 2019}}</ref>|group=lower-alpha|name=note_f}}\n| \n|-\n| 21\n| \n| \n| [[Dallas Wings]]\n| \n|-\n| 22\n| \n| \n| [[Los Angeles Sparks]]\n| \n|-\n| 23\n| \n| \n| [[Connecticut Sun]]\n| \n|-\n| 24\n| \n| \n| [[Washington Mystics]]\n| \n|}\n\n===Third round===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n|-\n! width=30|Pick\n! width=333|Player\n! width=200|Nationality\n! width=383|WNBA Team\n! width=333|School/Club Team/Country\n|-\n| 25\n| \n| \n| [[Atlanta Dream]]\n| \n|-\n| 26\n| \n| \n| [[New York Liberty]]\n| \n|-\n| 27\n| \n| \n| [[Atlanta Dream]]{{refn|The Wings traded this pick to Atlanta for [[Imani McGee-Stafford]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ajc.com/sports/basketball/dream-trade-center-imani-mcgee-stafford-dallas/iZJSTdXdaRiLfAbs2qgG1K/|title=Dream trade center Imani McGee-Stafford to Dallas|work=Atlanta Journal Constitution|date=May 16, 2019|accessdate=May 17, 2019}}</ref>|group=lower-alpha|name=note_g}}\n| \n|-\n| 28\n| \n| \n| [[Indiana Fever]]\n| \n|-\n| 29\n| \n| \n| [[Phoenix Mercury]]\n| \n|-\n| 30\n| \n| \n| [[Chicago Sky]]{{refn|The Lynx traded this pick to Chicago for [[Alaina Coates]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://sky.wnba.com/news/sky-acquire-2020-third-round-pick-from-minnesota-lynx/|title=Sky Acquire 2020 Third-Round Pick From Minnesota Lynx|website=wnba.com|publisher=WNBA|date=May 21, 2019|accessdate=May 21, 2019}}</ref>|group=lower-alpha|name=note_h}}\n| \n|-\n| 31\n| \n| \n| [[Seattle Storm]]\n| \n|-\n| 32\n| \n| \n| [[Chicago Sky]]\n| \n|-\n| 33\n| \n| \n| [[Las Vegas Aces]]\n| \n|-\n| 34\n| \n| \n| [[Los Angeles Sparks]]\n| \n|-\n| 35\n| \n| \n| [[Connecticut Sun]]\n| \n|-\n| 36\n| \n| \n| [[Washington Mystics]]\n| \n|}\n\n== Footnotes ==\n{{reflist|group=lower-alpha}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{WNBA Drafts}}\n\n[[Category:Women's National Basketball Association Draft]]\n[[Category:April 2020 sports events in the United States|WNBA draft]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox sports draft\n| league        = WNBA\n| teams         = 12\n| name          = 2020 WNBA Draft\n| image         =\n| imagesize     =\n| caption       =\n| sport         = Basketball\n| date          = April 17, 2020\n| location      = Digital\n| network       = [[WNBA on ESPN|ESPN]]\n| first_pick    = \n| prev          = [[2019 WNBA draft|2019]]\n| next          = [[2021 WNBA draft|2021]]\n}}\n\nThe '''2020 WNBA draft''' will be the [[WNBA|league]]'s draft for the [[2020 WNBA season]]. A draft lottery was held on September 17, 2019 and the [[New York Liberty]] were awarded the first overall pick in the draft.<ref name=\"lottery\">{{cite web|url=https://www.wnba.com/news/wnba-draft-lottery-presented-by-state-farm-to-take-place-on-sept-17-on-espn2/|title=WNBA Draft Lottery Presented By State Farm To Take Place on Sept. 17 on ESPN2|website=wnba.com|date=September 12, 2019|accessdate=September 12, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"draw\">{{cite web|url=https://www.wnba.com/news/new-york-liberty-wins-top-pick-in-2020-wnba-draft-presented-by-state-farm/|title=New York Liberty Win Top Pick In WNBA Draft 2020 Presented By State Farm\u00ae|website=wnba.com|publisher=WNBA|date=September 17, 2019|accessdate=September 17, 2019}}</ref> Due to the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States|coronavirus pandemic]] the draft will be held virtually without players, guests, and the media on-site.  The draft will be televised as planned.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wnba.com/news/wnba-draft-2020-to-be-held-april-17/|title=WNBA Draft 2020 Presented By State Farm To Be Held As Scheduled On April 17|publisher=WNBA|website=wnba.com|date=March 26, 2020|accessdate=March 26, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Draft lottery==\n\nThe lottery selection to determine the order of the top four picks in the 2020 Draft took place during halftime of the [[2019 Connecticut Sun season|Connecticut Sun's]] semifinal game against the [[2019 Los Angeles Sparks season|Los Angeles Sparks]] on September 17, 2019 and was televised on [[WNBA on ESPN|ESPN2]].  Four non-playoff teams qualified for the lottery drawing: [[Indiana Fever]], [[Dallas Wings]], [[New York Liberty]], and [[Atlanta Dream]].<ref name=\"lottery\"/>\n\n===Lottery chances===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center; width: 70%\"\n! Team\n! Combined 2018\u20132019 Record\n! Lottery Chances (out of 1000)\n|-\n| '''[[New York Liberty]]''' \u2013 WON\n| '''17\u201351'''\n| '''442'''\n|-\n| [[Indiana Fever]]\n| 19\u201349\n| 276\n|-\n| [[Dallas Wings]]\n| 25\u201343\n| 178\n|-\n| [[Atlanta Dream]]\n| 31\u201337\n| 104\n|}\n\nThe lottery odds were based on combined records from the 2018 and 2019 WNBA seasons. In the drawing, 14 balls numbered 1\u201314 are placed in a lottery machine and mixed.  Four balls are drawn to determine a four-digit combination.  The team assigned that four-ball combination receives the No. 1 pick.  The four balls are then placed back into the machine and the process is repeated to determine the second pick.  The two teams whose numerical combinations do not come up in the lottery will select in the inverse order of their two-year cumulative record.<ref name=\"lottery\"/>\n\nThe order of selection for the remainder of the first round as well as the second and third rounds is determined by inverse order of the teams\u2019 respective regular-season records solely from 2019.<ref name=\"lottery\"/>\n\nThe lottery was won by the [[New York Liberty]], who had the best chance to win the lottery.  The [[Dallas Wings]] were awarded the second pick, followed by the [[Indiana Fever]] and finally the [[Atlanta Dream]].<ref name=\"draw\"/>\n\n==Eligibility==\nUnder the current [[collective bargaining agreement]] (CBA) between the WNBA and its players union, draft eligibility for players not defined as \"international\" requires the following to be true:<ref>{{cite web|url=https://wnbpa.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/01/WNBA-WNBPA-CBA-2020-2027.pdf |title=Article XIII, Section 1: Player Eligibility |work=2020 Women's National Basketball Association Collective Bargaining Agreement |pages=110\u201311 |publisher=Women's National Basketball Players Association |accessdate=February 28, 2020}}</ref>\n* The player's 22nd birthday falls during the calendar year of the draft. For this draft, the cutoff birth date is December 31, 1998.\n* She has either:\n** completed her college eligibility;\n** received a bachelor's degree, or is scheduled to receive such in the 3 months following the draft; or\n** is at least 4 years removed from high school graduation.\n\nA player who is scheduled to receive her bachelor's degree within 3 months of the draft date, and is younger than the cutoff age, is only eligible if the calendar year of the draft is no earlier than the fourth after her high school graduation.\n\nPlayers with remaining college eligibility who meet the cutoff age must notify the WNBA headquarters of their intent to enter the draft no later than 10 days before the draft date, and must renounce any remaining college eligibility to do so. A separate notification timetable is provided for players involved in postseason tournaments (most notably the [[NCAA Division I Women's Basketball Tournament|NCAA Division I tournament]]); those players must declare for the draft within 24 hours of their final game. This second timetable proved to be moot due to the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States|coronavirus]]-induced cancellation of the [[2020 NCAA Division I Women's Basketball Tournament|2020 NCAA Tournament]].\n\n\"International players\" are defined as those for whom all of the following is true:\n* Born and currently residing outside the U.S.\n* Never \"exercised intercollegiate basketball eligibility\" in the U.S.\n\nFor \"international players\", the eligibility age is 20, also measured on December 31 of the year of the draft.\n\nThree players with remaining college eligibility, all of whom were juniors in the 2019\u201320 college season, have so far declared for the draft:\n* [[Satou Sabally]] of [[Oregon Ducks women's basketball|Oregon]] announced on February 20 that she would enter the draft upon the end of Oregon's 2019\u201320 season. Although a [[Germany|German]] citizen, she falls under the rules for U.S. players not only because of playing at Oregon, but also via her birth in [[New York City]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.espn.com/womens-college-basketball/story/_/id/28743871/oregon-junior-satou-sabally-enter-wnba-draft-season |title=Oregon junior Satou Sabally to enter WNBA draft after season |first=Holly |last=Rowe |authorlink=Holly Rowe |website=ESPN.com |date=February 20, 2020 |accessdate=March 15, 2020}}</ref>\n* [[Megan Walker]] of [[UConn Huskies women's basketball|UConn]] declared on March 14, after the cancellation of the NCAA tournament.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.yahoo.com/sports/uconns-walker-forgo-senior-enter-wnba-draft-182122819--ncaaw.html |title=UConn's Walker to forgo senior year, enter WNBA draft |agency=Associated Press |website=Yahoo Sports |date=March 14, 2020 |accessdate=March 15, 2020}}</ref>\n* [[Chennedy Carter]] of [[Texas A&M Aggies women's basketball|Texas A&M]] declared on March 29.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.espn.com/wnba/story/_/id/28968887/texas-star-chennedy-carter-declares-wnba-draft |title=Texas A&M star Chennedy Carter declares for WNBA draft |first=Mechelle |last=Voepel |website=ESPN.com |date=March 29, 2020 |accessdate=March 29, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Draft==\n\n===First round===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n|-\n! width=30|Pick\n! width=333|Player\n! width=200|Nationality\n! width=383|WNBA Team\n! width=333|School/Club Team/Country\n|-\n| 1\n| \n| \n| [[New York Liberty]]\n| \n|-\n| 2\n| \n| \n| [[Dallas Wings]]\n| \n|-\n| 3\n| \n| \n| [[Indiana Fever]]\n| \n|-\n| 4\n| \n| \n| [[Atlanta Dream]]\n| \n|-\n| 5\n| \n| \n| [[Dallas Wings]]{{refn|The Mercury traded the fifth and seventh picks in the 2020 draft, along with a future first-round pick, to Dallas for [[Skylar Diggins-Smith]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wnba.com/news/four-time-wnba-all-star-acquired-by-phoenix-in-sign-and-trade-deal/|title=Four-time WNBA All-Star Acquired by Phoenix in Sign and Trade Deal|website=wnba.com|publisher=WNBA|date=February 12, 2020|accessdate=February 12, 2020}}</ref>|group=lower-alpha|name=note_j}}\n| \n|-\n| 6\n| \n| \n| [[Minnesota Lynx]]\n| \n|-\n| 7\n| \n| \n| [[Dallas Wings]]{{refn|The Storm traded the eleventh pick to Connecticut for the seventh pick in the Draft.  Additionally Seattle received [[Morgan Tuck]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://storm.wnba.com/news/seattle-completes-trade-with-connecticut-acquires-morgan-tuck/|title=Seattle Completes Trade With Connecticut, Acquires Morgan Tuck|website=wnba.com|publisher=WNBA|date=February 10, 2020|accessdate=February 11, 2020}}</ref>|group=lower-alpha|name=note_a}},{{refn|The Sun traded the seventh and tenth pick in the Draft, along with a 2021 First Round Pick to Phoenix for [[DeWanna Bonner]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.azcentral.com/story/sports/wnba/mercury/2020/02/11/phoenix-mercury-all-star-dewanna-bonner-traded-connecticut-sun/4720920002/|title=Phoenix Mercury All-Star DeWanna Bonner traded to Connecticut Sun|website=azcentral.com|publisher=Arizona Republic|first=Jeff|last=Metcalfe|date=February 11, 2020|accessdate=February 11, 2020}}</ref>|group=lower-alpha|name=note_i}},{{refn|group=lower-alpha|name=note_j}}\n| \n|-\n| 8\n| \n| \n| [[Chicago Sky]]\n| \n|-\n| 9\n| \n| \n| [[Dallas Wings]]{{refn|The Aces traded this pick, their second round pick, [[Moriah Jefferson]], and [[Isabelle Harrison]] to Dallas for [[Liz Cambage]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/wnba/story/_/id/26761115/wings-trade-mvp-runner-cambage-aces|title=Wings trade MVP runner-up Cambage to Aces|website=espn.com|publisher=ESPN|date=May 16, 2019|accessdate=May 16, 2019}}</ref>|group=lower-alpha|name=note_b}}\n| \n|-\n| 10\n| \n| \n| [[Phoenix Mercury]]{{refn|The Sparks traded this pick to Connecticut for [[Chiney Ogwumike]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wnba.com/news/sparks-acquire-2014-no-1-overall-pick-chiney-ogwumike/|title=Sparks Acquire 2014 No. 1 Overall Pick Chiney Ogwumike|website=wnba.com|publisher=WNBA|date=April 27, 2019|accessdate=April 27, 2019}}</ref>|group=lower-alpha|name=note_c}},{{refn|group=lower-alpha|name=note_i}}\n| \n|-\n| 11\n| \n| \n| [[Seattle Storm]]{{refn|group=lower-alpha|name=note_a}}\n| \n|-\n| 12\n| \n| \n| [[Washington Mystics]]\n| \n|}\n\n===Second round===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n|-\n! width=30|Pick\n! width=333|Player\n! width=200|Nationality\n! width=383|WNBA Team\n! width=333|School/Club Team/Country\n|-\n| 13\n| \n| \n| [[Atlanta Dream]]\n| \n|-\n| 14\n| \n| \n| [[Indiana Fever]]{{refn|The Liberty traded this pick to Minnesota for [[Tanisha Wright]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://liberty.wnba.com/news/liberty-acquires-guard-tanisha-wright-in-exchange-for-2020-second-round-pick/|title=Liberty Acquires Guard Tanisha Wright in Exchange for 2020 Second Round Pic