{"title_page": "Eunuchs in popular culture", "text_new": "{{Refimprove|date=March 2020}}\n\n\n'''[[Eunuch]]s''' have appeared in many films, works of [[literature]], and in [[popular culture]].\n\n==Anime and manga==\n* In the Japanese anime ''[[Code Geass: Lelouch of the Rebellion]]'' (R2), the de facto rulers of the communist Chinese Federation comprise a group of eight eunuchs called \"High Eunuchs\".\n* In the manga ''[[Red River (manga)|Red River]]'', one of the main villains, Urhi, is a eunuch.\n\n==Comics==\n* The titular character of ''[[That Yellow Bastard]]'' (February\u2013July 1996), a limited comic book series, the sixth in Dark Horse Comics' Sin City series, is a eunuch. (The series was adapted as a film, titled ''[[Sin City (film)|Sin City]]'' (2005), also known as ''Frank Miller's Sin City''.)\n\n==Films==\n* Eunuchs appear often as villains in [[Hong Kong]] [[kung fu]] and [[wuxia]] films set in ancient China. For example, the films ''[[Dragon Inn]]'' (''Xin long men ke zhan''), ''[[Butterfly and Sword (film)|Butterfly and Sword]]'' (''Xin liu xing hu die jian''), and ''[[A Touch of Zen]]'' (''Hsia nu'') all feature a eunuch or a group of eunuchs as the main villain. A popular eunuch villain used in ancient China stories is Eunuch Wei, who is based on a historical figure named [[Wei Zhongxian]]. Eunuch villains are usually in charge of powerful political posts, such as being the leader of the East Chamber.\n* In [[Mel Brooks]]'s comedy ''[[History of the World, Part I]]'' (1981), under the section of \"The Roman Empire\", an entire scene is devoted to a joke about eunuchs, the length of African genitals, and the song, \"[[Caldonia]]\"; all rolled into one.\n* In the Disney animated film ''[[Mulan (1998 film)|Mulan]]'' (1998), the character Chi-Fu is a royal advisor that has been attached to Captain Li Shang's forces.  Due to his nature as a royal advisor to the Emperor of China and the historical nature of the film, he would be assumed to be a eunuch.   \n* ''[[The Last Eunuch]]'' (1988), a Chinese biographical film directed by [[Zhang Zhiliang]], tells the story of [[Sun Yaoting]], who saw the last royal palace's extravagant lifestyle and experienced the breakdown of the last imperial empire and felt the new changes brought by the new age.\n* The film ''[[Farinelli (film)|Farinelli]]'' (1994) is about the castrato singer [[Farinelli]].\n* The documentary film ''Bombay Eunuch'' (2001) examines the changing role of India's [[Hijra (South Asia)|hijras]], some of whom are also eunuchs.\n* The documentary film ''American Eunuchs'' (2003) investigates the underworld of modern eunuchs in America.\n* In the film ''[[One Night With the King]]'' (2006), [[Esther|Hadassah]]'s (Esther's) would-be boyfriend, Jesse, is captured by the Persian empire and castrated.\n* The documentary film ''Kiss the Moon'' (2010), set in Pakistan, portrays three generations of eunuchs examining the ancient rituals and religious beliefs surrounding their community.\n* ''Nilkantho'' treats the plight of the Indian hijras with sensitivity.{{cn|date=March 2019}}\n* In ''[[Murder 2]]'' (2011), by [[Emraan Hashmi]] , the antagonist castrates himself and becomes an eunuch.\n\n==Games==\n* In the video game ''[[The Witcher 3: Wild Hunt]]'' (2015), the loyal servant and bookie of head Redanian Intelligence Sigismund Dijkstra is a eunuch, called Happen the Eunuch. He takes care of the Bathhouse in Novigrad, which is open to both sexes.\n\n==Literature==\n* ''[[The Alteration]]'' by [[Kingsley Amis]] is an \"alternative history\" set in 20th-century England about a boy soprano and eunuch. \n* Several tales of the ''[[Arabian Nights]]'' focus on eunuchs.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.globusz.com/ebooks/1001v2/00000014.htm |title=Tale of the First Eunuch, Bukhayt |website=Globusz.com |date= |accessdate=2014-04-24}}</ref>\n* For the greater part of [[Iain Banks]]' novel ''[[The Wasp Factory]]'' (1984), the 16-year-old narrator [[Frank Cauldhame]] claims to be a eunuch, the result of being savaged by a dog when he was an infant. At the novel's climax, Frank discovers that he was, in fact, born female.\n* The character of the Pardoner in [[Geoffrey Chaucer]]'s ''[[The Canterbury Tales]]'', is implied to be a eunuch or homosexual.\n*Being proud of not being a eunuch is the subject of the song \"[[At Least You're Not a Eunuch]]\" in the play ''[[Life and Death in Jaffna]] (The Musical!)'' by [[Edward Cress]]\n* The Queen [[Salmissra]], in [[David Eddings]]' ''[[The Belgariad]]'' and ''[[The Malloreon]]'', is only allowed to be served by eunuchs. Her chief eunuch, Sadi, becomes a principal character in ''[[The Malloreon]]'', and is referred to in ''The Prophecy'' as \"The Man who is no Man.\"\n* Three best-selling [[crime fiction|crime novels]] by [[Jason Goodwin]], ''[[The Janissary Tree]]'' and its sequels, ''[[The Snake Stone]]'' and ''The Bellini Card'', are set in [[Istanbul]] in the 1830s, chronicle the investigations of [[Yashim Togalu]], a Turkish eunuch detective to the Sultan's royal court, in the [[Ottoman Empire]] of the 1830s.\n* Christopher Harris' historical novel ''[[Memoirs of a Byzantine Eunuch]]'' (2002) features a eunuch.\n* In [[Robert E. Howard]]'s short story \"[[The Scarlet Citadel]]\", the main antagonist has a eunuch prison guard named Shukeli, in whom normal human passions have been replaced by extreme sadism.\n* The eunuch Manan is a major character in ''[[The Tombs of Atuan]]'', the second book from [[Ursula K. Le Guin]]'s [[Earthsea]] series. The story largely takes place in a large convent where no men are allowed, so a number of other eunuchs are mentioned.\n* The Vampire Eli in [[John Ajvide Lindqvist]]'s novel ''[[Let the Right One In (novel)|Let The Right One In]]'' is a eunuch. However, this detail is not made abundantly clear in the book's [[Let the Right One In (film)|eponymous 2008 film adaptation]].\n* [[George R. R. Martin]]'s fantasy series ''[[A Song of Ice and Fire]]'' and its TV adaptation, ''[[Game of Thrones]]'', features numerous eunuchs, including:  the eunuch [[Varys]] (also called the Spider), a court official bearing the title of Master of Whisperers, the equivalent of the real world [[spymaster]]; [[Theon Greyjoy]], who is implied to have been castrated while held prisoner; and the Unsullied, elite eunuch soldiers, who are also greatly featured in the books.\n* Eunuchs feature prominently in [[Montesquieu]]'s novel ''[[Lettres Persanes]]'' (1722) about Persian visitors to 18th-century France.\n* A historical mystery series{{which|date=March 2019}} written by [[Mary Reed]] and [[Eric Mayer]], beginning in 1999, details investigations carried out by John, the eunuch [[Lord Chamberlain]] to [[Emperor Justinian I]], in and around the sixth-century imperial court in [[Constantinople]].\n* Bagoas, the eunuch favorite of [[Alexander the Great]]'s, is the main character and narrator of ''[[The Persian Boy]]'' (1972), an historical novel by [[Mary Renault]]. \n*Castrati singers in 18th-century Italy are the main characters of Anne Rice's novel ''[[Cry to Heaven]]''.\n* [[Kim Stanley Robinson]]'s historical [[science fiction]] novel ''[[The Years of Rice and Salt]]'' (2002) features many eunuchs in its opening section, including the character Kyu and the historical Chinese admiral [[Zheng He]].\n* Sazed, a major character in [[Brandon Sanderson]]'s [[Mistborn|Mistborn trilogy]], was made a eunuch at a young age. He eventually ascends to godhood, becoming an entity called Harmony, who was castrated as a punishment while a slave.\n* In [[William Shakespeare]]'s play ''[[Twelfth Night]]'', Viola initially decides to disguise herself as a eunuch named Cesario in order to serve Duke Orsino.\n* Wilbur Smith's Egyptian series of novels about ancient Egypt, beginning with ''[[River God]]'' (1991), follow the adventures of a talented eunuch named Taita.\n*''[[Eunuchus]]'' (''The Eunuch'') is a comedy by the Roman playwright [[Terence]].\n* One of the characters that [[Voltaire]]'s ''[[Candide]]'' meets on his adventures is a eunuch.\n* In ''[[The Country Wife]]'' (1675) by William Wycherley, the main character, Mr. Horner, pretends to be a man turned eunuch by impotence caused by [[syphilis]], in order to gain access to the bedrooms of married women.\n* The society described in [[Rieko Yoshihara]]'s Japanese novel (and later anime series) ''[[Ai no Kusabi]]'' has within its caste system \"Furniture\", or eunuchs who act as servants to the highest social class. The character Katze was once Furniture but now works on the black market.\n\n==Music==\n* The punk rock band the [[Descendents]] wrote a song about a eunuch called \"Eunuch Boy\", which was on their 1996 comeback album ''[[Everything Sucks (Descendents album)|Everything Sucks]]''.\n\n==Television==\n* In the TV show ''[[Major Dad]]'', a eunuch was in charge of the [[security]] wives of Emir of Katodd.\n* In the ''[[Red Dwarf]]'' episode \"Marooned\", Rimmer is said to have been [[Alexander the Great]]'s chief eunuch in a past life.\n* The character [[List of recurring characters from The Mighty Boosh#Naboo the Enigma|Naboo the Enigma]], from the British comedy act and television series ''[[The Mighty Boosh]]'', is a eunuch.\n* In the [[HBO]] show ''[[Game of Thrones]]'' supporting character [[Varys]] is a eunuch, as are the elite warriors of the Unsullied.\n* In the British Television programme \"[[Peep Show (TV series)|Peep Show]]\", Mark is described as a Eunuch by Big Suze in the episode \"Sisterning\",\n* In the South Korean drama [[Love in the Moonlight|''Love in the Moonlight'']], one of the main characters is a girl who's disguised as a eunuch.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Eunuchs In Popular Culture}}\n[[Category:Topics in popular culture]]\n", "text_old": "{{Refimprove|date=March 2020}}\n\n\n'''[[Eunuch]]s''' have appeared in many films, works of [[literature]], and in [[popular culture]].\n\n==Anime and manga==\n* In the Japanese anime ''[[Code Geass: Lelouch of the Rebellion]]'' (R2), the de facto rulers of the communist Chinese Federation comprise a group of eight eunuchs called \"High Eunuchs\".\n* In the manga ''[[Red River (manga)|Red River]]'', one of the main villains, Urhi, is a eunuch.\n\n==Comics==\n* The titular character of ''[[That Yellow Bastard]]'' (February\u2013July 1996), a limited comic book series, the sixth in Dark Horse Comics' Sin City series, is a eunuch. (The series was adapted as a film, titled ''[[Sin City (film)|Sin City]]'' (2005), also known as ''Frank Miller's Sin City''.)\n\n==Films==\n* Eunuchs appear often as villains in [[Hong Kong]] [[kung fu]] and [[wuxia]] films set in ancient China. For example, the films ''[[Dragon Inn]]'' (''Xin long men ke zhan''), ''[[Butterfly and Sword (film)|Butterfly and Sword]]'' (''Xin liu xing hu die jian''), and ''[[A Touch of Zen]]'' (''Hsia nu'') all feature a eunuch or a group of eunuchs as the main villain. A popular eunuch villain used in ancient China stories is Eunuch Wei, who is based on a historical figure named [[Wei Zhongxian]]. Eunuch villains are usually in charge of powerful political posts, such as being the leader of the East Chamber.\n* In [[Mel Brooks]]'s comedy ''[[History of the World, Part I]]'' (1981), under the section of \"The Roman Empire\", an entire scene is devoted to a joke about eunuchs, the length of African genitals, and the song, \"[[Caldonia]]\"; all rolled into one.\n* In the Disney animated film ''[[Mulan (1998 film)|Mulan]]'' (1998), the character Chi-Fu is a royal advisor that has been attached to Captain Li Shang's forces.  Due to his nature as a royal advisor to the Emperor of China and the historical nature of the film, he would be assumed to be a eunuch.   \n* ''[[The Last Eunuch]]'' (1988), a Chinese biographical film directed by [[Zhang Zhiliang]], tells the story of [[Sun Yaoting]], who saw the last royal palace's extravagant lifestyle and experienced the breakdown of the last imperial empire and felt the new changes brought by the new age.\n* The film ''[[Farinelli (film)|Farinelli]]'' (1994) is about the castrato singer [[Farinelli]].\n* The documentary film ''Bombay Eunuch'' (2001) examines the changing role of India's [[Hijra (South Asia)|hijras]], some of whom are also eunuchs.\n* The documentary film ''American Eunuchs'' (2003) investigates the underworld of modern eunuchs in America.\n* In the film ''[[One Night With the King]]'' (2006), [[Esther|Hadassah]]'s (Esther's) would-be boyfriend, Jesse, is captured by the Persian empire and castrated.\n* The documentary film ''Kiss the Moon'' (2010), set in Pakistan, portrays three generations of eunuchs examining the ancient rituals and religious beliefs surrounding their community.\n* ''Nilkantho'' treats the plight of the Indian hijras with sensitivity.{{cn|date=March 2019}}\n* In ''[[Murder 2]]'' (2011), by [[Emraan Hashmi]] , the antagonist castrates himself and becomes an eunuch.\n\n==Games==\n* In the video game ''[[The Witcher 3: Wild Hunt]]'' (2015), the loyal servant and bookie of head Redanian Intelligence Sigismund Dijkstra is a eunuch, called Happen the Eunuch. He takes care of the Bathhouse in Novigrad, which is open to both sexes.\n\n==Literature==\n* ''[[The Alteration]]'' by [[Kingsley Amis]] is an \"alternative history\" set in 20th-century England about a boy soprano and eunuch. \n* Several tales of the ''[[Arabian Nights]]'' focus on eunuchs.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.globusz.com/ebooks/1001v2/00000014.htm |title=Tale of the First Eunuch, Bukhayt |website=Globusz.com |date= |accessdate=2014-04-24}}</ref>\n* For the greater part of [[Iain Banks]]' novel ''[[The Wasp Factory]]'' (1984), the 16-year-old narrator [[Frank Cauldhame]] claims to be a eunuch, the result of being savaged by a dog when he was an infant. At the novel's climax, Frank discovers that he was, in fact, born female.\n* The character of the Pardoner in [[Geoffrey Chaucer]]'s ''[[The Canterbury Tales]]'', is implied to be a eunuch or homosexual.\n*Being proud of not being a eunuch is the subject of the song \"[[At Least You're Not a Eunuch]]\" in the play ''[[Life and Death in Jaffna]] (The Musical!)'' by [[Edward Cress]]\n* The Queen [[Salmissra]], in [[David Eddings]]' ''[[The Belgariad]]'' and ''[[The Malloreon]]'', is only allowed to be served by eunuchs. Her chief eunuch, Sadi, becomes a principal character in ''[[The Malloreon]]'', and is referred to in ''The Prophecy'' as \"The Man who is no Man.\"\n* Three best-selling [[crime fiction|crime novels]] by [[Jason Goodwin]], ''[[The Janissary Tree]]'' and its sequels, ''[[The Snake Stone]]'' and ''The Bellini Card'', are set in [[Istanbul]] in the 1830s, chronicle the investigations of [[Yashim Togalu]], a Turkish eunuch detective to the Sultan's royal court, in the [[Ottoman Empire]] of the 1830s.\n* Christopher Harris' historical novel ''[[Memoirs of a Byzantine Eunuch]]'' (2002) features a eunuch.\n* In [[Robert E. Howard]]'s short story \"[[The Scarlet Citadel]]\", the main antagonist has a eunuch prison guard named Shukeli, in whom normal human passions have been replaced by extreme sadism.\n* The eunuch Manan is a major character in ''[[The Tombs of Atuan]]'', the second book from [[Ursula K. Le Guin]]'s [[Earthsea]] series. The story largely takes place in a large convent where no men are allowed, so a number of other eunuchs are mentioned.\n* The Vampire Eli in [[John Ajvide Lindqvist]]'s novel ''[[Let the Right One In (novel)|Let The Right One In]]'' is a eunuch. However, this detail is not made abundantly clear in the book's [[Let the Right One In (film)|eponymous 2008 film adaptation]].\n* [[George R. R. Martin]]'s fantasy series ''[[A Song of Ice and Fire]]'' and its TV adaptation, ''[[Game of Thrones]]'', features numerous eunuchs, including:  the eunuch [[Varys]] (also called the Spider), a court official bearing the title of Master of Whisperers, the equivalent of the real world [[spymaster]]; [[Theon Greyjoy]], who is implied to have been castrated while held prisoner; and the Unsullied, elite eunuch soldiers, who are also greatly featured in the books.\n* Eunuchs feature prominently in [[Montesquieu]]'s novel ''[[Lettres Persanes]]'' (1722) about Persian visitors to 18th-century France.\n* A historical mystery series{{which|date=March 2019}} written by [[Mary Reed]] and [[Eric Mayer]], beginning in 1999, details investigations carried out by John, the eunuch [[Lord Chamberlain]] to [[Emperor Justinian I]], in and around the sixth-century imperial court in [[Constantinople]].\n* Bagoas, the eunuch favorite of [[Alexander the Great]]'s, is the main character and narrator of ''[[The Persian Boy]]'' (1972), an historical novel by [[Mary Renault]]. \n*Castrati singers in 18th-century Italy are the main characters of Anne Rice's novel ''[[Cry to Heaven]]''.\n* [[Kim Stanley Robinson]]'s historical [[science fiction]] novel ''[[The Years of Rice and Salt]]'' (2002) features many eunuchs in its opening section, including the character Kyu and the historical Chinese admiral [[Zheng He]].\n* Sazed, a major character in [[Brandon Sanderson]]'s [[Mistborn|Mistborn trilogy]], was made a eunuch at a young age. He eventually ascends to godhood, becoming an entity called Harmony, who was castrated as a punishment while a slave.\n* In [[William Shakespeare]]'s play ''[[Twelfth Night]]'', Viola initially decides to disguise herself as a eunuch named Cesario in order to serve Duke Orsino.\n* Wilbur Smith's Egyptian series of novels about ancient Egypt, beginning with ''[[River God]]'' (1991), follow the adventures of a talented eunuch named Taita.\n*''[[Eunuchus]]'' (''The Eunuch'') is a comedy by the Roman playwright [[Terence]].\n* One of the characters that [[Voltaire]]'s ''[[Candide]]'' meets on his adventures is a eunuch.\n* In ''[[The Country Wife]]'' (1675) by William Wycherley, the main character, Mr. Horner, pretends to be a man turned eunuch by impotence caused by [[syphilis]], in order to gain access to the bedrooms of married women.\n* The society described in [[Rieko Yoshihara]]'s Japanese novel (and later anime series) ''[[Ai no Kusabi]]'' has within its caste system \"Furniture\", or eunuchs who act as servants to the highest social class. The character Katze was once Furniture but now works on the black market.\n\n==Music==\n* The punk rock band the [[Descendents]] wrote a song about a eunuch called \"Eunuch Boy\", which was on their 1996 comeback album ''[[Everything Sucks (Descendents album)|Everything Sucks]]''.\n\n==Television==\n* In the TV show ''[[Major Dad]]'', a eunuch was in charge of the [[security]] wives of Emir of Katodd.\n* In the ''[[Red Dwarf]]'' episode \"Marooned\", Rimmer is said to have been [[Alexander the Great]]'s chief eunuch in a past life.\n* The character [[List of recurring characters from The Mighty Boosh#Naboo the Enigma|Naboo the Enigma]], from the British comedy act and television series ''[[The Mighty Boosh]]'', is a eunuch.\n* In the [[HBO]] show ''[[Game of Thrones]]'' supporting character [[Varys]] is a eunuch, as are the elite warriors of the Unsullied.\n* In the British Television programme \"[[Peep Show (TV series)|Peep Show]]\", Mark is described as a Eunuch by Big Suze in the episode \"Sisterning\",\n* In the Korean drama [[Love in the Moonlight|''Love in the Moonlight'']], one of the main characters is a girl who's disguised as a eunuch.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Eunuchs In Popular Culture}}\n[[Category:Topics in popular culture]]\n", "name_user": "OkJihui22", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eTelevision", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Eunuchs_in_popular_culture"}
{"title_page": "Gwen Shamblin Lara", "text_new": "{{Infobox writer <!-- for more information see [[:Template:Infobox writer/doc]] -->\n| name = Gwen Shamblin Lara\n| image = Gwen Shamblin 2018 (cropped).jpg\n| image_size = \n| caption = \n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|mf=yes|1955|02|18}}\n| birth_place = [[Memphis, Tennessee]], U.S.\n| occupation = Author and Registered Dietician\n| residence = [[Brentwood, Tennessee]]\n| spouse = {{marriage|David Shamblin|1978|2018|reason=divorced}}<br>{{marriage|[[Joe Lara]]|2018}}\n| children = Michael Shamblin,<ref>{{cite web |title=www.michaelshamblin.com |url=http://www.michaelshamblin.com/about/ |website=michaelshamblin.com}}</ref> Elizabeth Shamblin Hannah<ref>{{cite web |title=gwenshamblinbooks.com |url=http://gwenshamblinbooks.com/bio/ |website=gwenshamblinbooks.com}}</ref>\n| genre = [[Self-help]], [[Non-fiction]]\n| movement = \n| influences = \n| influenced = \n| website = {{URL|http://www.gwenshamblin.com/}}\n}}\n'''Gwen Shamblin Lara''' is an American non-fiction author and founder of ''The Weigh Down Workshop'' and founder of the Remnant Fellowship Church. The most distinctive aspect of her writing is its combination of weight loss programs with [[Christianity]].\n\n==Early life==\nGwen earned an [[undergraduate degree]] in [[Dietitian|dietetics]] from [[University of Tennessee]], in [[Knoxville, Tennessee|Knoxville]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://lib.williamson-tn.org/Local_Authors/S.htm#_Shamblin,_Gwen|title=Williamson County Local Authors|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060131093440/http://lib.williamson-tn.org/Local_Authors/S.htm#_Shamblin,_Gwen|archive-date=2006-01-31|url-status=dead|accessdate=2007-04-25|work=Williamson County Library}}</ref> and then her master's degree in food and nutrition<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=|title=Frazee woman shares personal weight loss story|last=Thorp|first=Lori Frazer|date=1998-01-08|work=Frazee Forum|access-date=}}</ref> from the [[University of Memphis|Memphis State University]]. She is a [[Dietitian|registered dietitian]],<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/203907872/|title=Unorthodox diet plan targeted at teens|last=Gang|first=Christine Arpe|date=1988-04-13|work=Longview News-Journal|access-date=2017-07-05|page=4C|language=en}}</ref> consultant, and was a faculty member at the Memphis State University for five years.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|url=|title=Heart & Soul: An interview with Gwen Shamblin, founder of the Weigh Down Workshop|last=|first=|date=February 1999|work=Murfreesboro Matters|access-date=|issue=3|volume=1|page=3}}</ref> She also worked in the [[Tennessee Department of Health|state's health department]]<ref name=\":0\" /> for an additional five years.\n\n==Personal life==\nGwen was raised in a [[Church of Christ]] family.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Kennedy |first1=John W |title=Thomas Nelson pulls plug on Gwen Shamblin's book |url=http://www.bpnews.net/6481/thomas-nelson-pulls-plug-on-gwen-shamblins-book |accessdate=22 July 2019 |date=September 11, 2000}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/136209218/|title=Dieting religiously|last=White|first=Gaule|date=1997-03-31|work=Democrat and Chronicle|access-date=2017-07-05|page=3C|language=en}}</ref> She has two children and seven grandchildren.<ref name=\":7\">{{Cite news|url=|title=Women of the Year: Gwen Shamblin|last=Ieron|first=Julie-Allyson|date=January 2000|work=Clarity Magazine|access-date=}}</ref><ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web |title=remnantfellowship.org |url=http://www.remnantfellowship.org/Our-Leaders/Gwen-Shamblin |website=www.remnantfellowship.org}}</ref>and as of March 1996, Gwen lived with her family in Ashlawn, a historic mansion in [[Brentwood, Tennessee]], that was built in 1838.<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/113496856/|title=You could've had it, for $2.3 million|last=McCampbell|first=Candy|date=1996-03-11|work=The Tennessean|access-date=2017-07-05|page=1E|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.brentwood-tn.org/Modules/ShowDocument.aspx?documentid=417|title=Ashlawn|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100621073800/http://brentwood-tn.org/Modules/ShowDocument.aspx?documentid=417|archive-date=2010-06-21|url-status=dead|accessdate=2011-08-11|work=City of Brentwood}}</ref> In 2018 she married [[Joe Lara]]<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.gwenshamblin.com/about/|title=About - Gwen Shamblin|work=Gwen Shamblin|access-date=2018-08-28|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n== Ministry career ==\n\n===Weigh Down Workshop===\nGwen began her consulting practice in the area of weight control in 1980.<ref name=\":1\" /> She had struggled with her weight while attending school.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/local/1997/05/17/dieters-putting-their-faith-in-sustenance-of-the-spirit/d514bacc-c4b8-4eb9-a7fa-568354a44f68/|title=Dieters putting their faith in sustenance of the spirit|last=Hull|first=Dana|date=1997-05-17|work=The Washington Post|access-date=2017-07-05|language=en-US|issn=0190-8286}}</ref> She became \"convinced that [[genetics]], [[metabolism]] and [[behavior modification]] alone couldn't explain why some people were thin and others battled the bulge.\"<ref name=\":22\">{{cite news|url=|title=Divine Intervention|last=Spencer|first=Paula|date=1994-11-22|work=[[Woman's Day]]|access-date=|pages=76, 78}}</ref> In 1986, Gwen founded the Weigh Down Workshop,<ref name=\":32\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/112566660/|title=Churchgoers leaning on God to shed their unwanted pounds|last=Waddle|first=Ray|date=1994-02-27|work=The Tennessean|access-date=2017-07-05|page=2A|language=en}}</ref><ref name=\":42\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/113393691/|title=Weigh Down transfers love for food into love for God|last=Waddle|first=Ray|date=1996-07-03|work=The Tennessean|access-date=2017-07-05|pages=1B\u20132B|language=en}}</ref> a [[Dieting|weight loss program]] which has \u201cno forbidden foods, exercise regimen or weigh-ins,\u201d<ref name=\":52\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/205898521/|title=God is focus of weight-loss program|last=Associated Press|first=|date=1995-01-03|work=Battle Creek Enquirer|access-date=2017-07-05|page=4A|language=en}}</ref> and avoids \u201c[[A calorie is a calorie#Calorie counting|calorie counting]].\u201d<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/159455908/|title=The Weigh to the Lite|last=Whyche|first=Stephanie|date=1995-10-09|work=The News Journal|access-date=2017-07-05|pages=C1, C4|language=en}}</ref> As ''[[The Tennessean]]'' points out, the program lacks \u201csome basic elements,\u201d like exercise and guidance on food selection, as recommended by the [[Academy of Nutrition and Dietetics|American Dietetic Association]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/112841589/|title=Praying away the pounds|last=Quigley|first=Linda|date=1997-03-01|work=The Tennessean|access-date=2017-07-05|pages=1D, 4D|language=en}}</ref> According to ''[[The Philadelphia Inquirer]]'', \u201cthe Weigh Down Workshop attempts to help participants develop the discipline to eat only when they are hungry and to stop eating when they are full.\u201d<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/178355816/|title=Christian dieters saying faith can defeat fat|last=Holmes|first=Kristin E.|date=1996-05-06|work=The Philadelphia Inquirer|access-date=2017-07-05|pages=B1, B3|language=en}}</ref>\n\nGwen developed the program while working on her master's degree at Memphis State University.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/222544335/|title=Program helps dieters succeed|last=Kleczynski|first=Jennifer Coleridge|date=1995-04-21|work=Strictly Hunterdon|access-date=2017-07-05|publisher=The Courier-News|page=5|language=en}}</ref> As part of a counseling center,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/159376638/|title=Dieters seek help in religion|last=|first=|date=1997-04-13|work=The News Journal|access-date=2017-07-05|pages=J1, J7|language=en}}</ref> she held the first class in a mall in Memphis, Tennessee;<ref name=\":10\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/archives/nydn-features/wages-thin-putting-grace-meals-christian-diet-programs-reshaping-lives-article-1.792223|title=The wages of thin: By putting grace before meals, Christian diet programs are reshaping lives|last=Bell|first=Bill|date=1998-06-17|work=New York Daily News|access-date=2017-07-05|language=en}}</ref> the program was initially only offered as small classes in similar retail<ref name=\":11\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/138503800/|title=Weight-loss disciples are shedding the extra pounds through prayer|last=Graham|first=Jennifer|date=1994-12-07|work=Democrat and Chronicle|access-date=2017-07-05|pages=1C, 6C|language=en}}</ref> and other non-religious settings.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/77357120/|title=Weighty matters|last=Wells|first=Valerie|date=1995-05-06|work=Herald and Review|access-date=2017-07-05|language=en}}</ref> In 1991<ref name=\":32\" /><ref name=\":42\" /> or 1992, she began hosting the program at [[Bellevue Baptist Church]] located in the Memphis area.<ref name=\":8\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/113428692|title=In God's own image|last=Hill|first=Laura|date=1998-02-10|work=The Tennessean|access-date=2017-07-05|language=en}}</ref> The program consists of twelve-week seminars guided by video and audio tapes featuring Gwen.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.greensboro.com/faith-helps-some-people-lower-weight-way-down/article_e2d14ec6-826c-5669-abfa-fb62ec1e134b.html|title=Faith helps some people lower weight way down|last=Johnson II|first=Lucas L.|date=1996-07-18|work=Greensboro News & Record|access-date=2017-07-05|agency=The Associated Press|language=en}}</ref> The meetings consist of a group viewing of one of her videos, along with prayer and discussion.<ref name=\":122\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/lifestyle/1995/01/23/dieting-with-jesus/67735e60-9238-4b4c-9ea2-ae3391d2b677/|title=Dieting with Jesus|last=Rosenfeld|first=Megan|date=1995-01-23|work=The Washington Post|access-date=2017-07-05|language=en-US}}</ref> By 1994, the program quickly spread as far away as Europe and was offered in about 600 churches in at least 35 US States.<ref name=\":22\" />\n\nAccording to the [[Associated Press]], by January 1995, the program could be found in over 1,000 churches in forty-nine US States, as well as at locations in Britain and Canada;<ref name=\":52\" /> but by July 1996, the workshop was at about 5,000 churches, with close to ten percent located in Gwen's home-state of Tennessee.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/285568028|title=Program urges people to turn to God to shed pounds|last=Associated Press|first=|date=1996-07-26|work=The Daily Spectrum|access-date=2017-07-05|language=en}}</ref> As many as eight churches in Britain were hosting workshops by December 1996.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/258291780/|title=The divine diet|last=Brooks|first=Richard|date=1996-12-29|work=The Observer|access-date=2017-07-05|language=en}}</ref> Some participants in the US would also host meetings in their private homes.<ref name=\":32\" />\n\nIn 1996, Weigh Down, which consisted of a forty-person staff, began building a headquarters in [[Franklin, Tennessee]].<ref name=\":42\" /> The same year, Gwen Shamblin Lara and Weigh Down began hosting an annual summer convention, known as Desert Oasis, in the [[Nashville, Tennessee|Nashville]] area.<ref name=\":42\" /><ref name=\":9\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/205068421|title=Heavenly help|last=De La Cruz|first=Jessi|date=1999-03-19|work=Lansing State Journal|access-date=2017-07-05|language=en}}</ref>\n\nBy August 1998, Weigh Down was holding more than 21,000 classes with over 250,000 reported participants worldwide.<ref name=\":132\">{{Cite news|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1998-08-20/features/9808200388_1_gwen-shamblin-weigh-smaller-sizes|title=Christian Diet Programs: Nourishing The Spirit Is The Key To Slimming Down The Body|last=Lauerman|first=Connie|date=1998-08-20|work=Chicago Tribune|access-date=2017-07-05|language=en}}</ref> Weigh Down Workshop classes would eventually spread to all fifty US states<ref name=\":42\" /> and every continent,<ref name=\"Random House2\">{{cite web|url=http://www.randomhouse.com/author/results.pperl?authorid=27826|title=Random House|accessdate=2010-02-11}}</ref> becoming \"one of the most popular weight-loss programs in the world\" by mid-2000.<ref name=\":14\">{{cite news|url=|title=The Power to Change|last=Long|first=Marion|date=May 2000|work=Family Circle|access-date=|pages=58\u201359}}</ref> Gwen has also been traveling to other cities as part of the ''Rebuilding the Wall'' tour.<ref name=\":15\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.christianitytoday.com/ct/2002/december9/6.15.html|title=New Sect: Weigh Down guru Gwen Shamblin's Remnant Fellowship grows.|last=Kennedy|first=John W.|date=2002-12-09|work=Christianity Today|access-date=2017-07-05|language=en}}</ref>\n\nOther dietitians have questioned the soundness of Gwen's diet advice, which focuses on faith instead of healthy eating habits or exercise.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.redorbit.com/news/health/470079/god_is_their_weightloss_guru/index.html|title=God is Their Weight-Loss Guru|last=Morning News|first=Dallas|date=2006-04-14|accessdate=2007-04-09|newspaper=[[The Dallas Morning News]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.skinnyondiets.com/GwenShamblinsWeighDownWorkshop.html?b=8277&GCID=S15771x274&KEYWORD=gwen%20shamblin&gclid=CLK6suekgYwCFR05UQodDiLcwQ|title=Gwen Shamblin's Weigh Down Workshop|publisher=skinnyondiets.com|accessdate=2007-05-23|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070927075755/http://www.skinnyondiets.com/GwenShamblinsWeighDownWorkshop.html?b=8277&GCID=S15771x274&KEYWORD=gwen%20shamblin&gclid=CLK6suekgYwCFR05UQodDiLcwQ|archive-date=2007-09-27|url-status=dead}}</ref> In the book ''Born Again Bodies: Flesh and Spirit in American Christianity'', author Marie Griffith, a [[Princeton University]] associate professor of religion, examines the trend of religion-based dieting. Although critical of Gwen for using the Christianity label while building her business, Griffith credits her for the new wave of interest in creating \"a more holy body\", and substantial sections of the work examine Shamblin's movement.<ref name=\"griffith2004\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=dGtHZImY4lcC|title=Born Again Bodies: Flesh and Spirit in American Christianity|last=Griffith|first=R. Marie|date=2004-10-04|publisher=University of California Press|isbn=9780520938113|language=en}}</ref> Griffith notes, \"In Shamblin's world, people who don't lose weight often feel like failures. If they don't lose weight, it's a failure of discipline; it's a failure of obedience.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.princeton.edu/news/2005/01/27/religion-professor-examines-salvation-diet-phenomenon|title=Religion professor examines 'salvation by diet' phenomenon|last=Allen|first=Patricia|date=2005-01-27|work=News@Princeton|accessdate=2007-05-23|publisher=|pages=}}</ref> At the same time, Griffith's work places Shamblin's movement squarely within a historical tradition of perfecting one's body in order to be more [[Jesus|Christ]]-like, or fasting and dieting in order to feel closer to God.<ref name=\"griffith2004\" />\n\nIn 2001, NewsChannel 5, a local Nashville news station, aired a story entitled \"Is it a ministry or just big business?\", looking into how Weigh Down Workshop's money was spent. Towards the end of the interview, Gwen states that \"half of [the money] goes to the government, the other half goes to keep it going so someone else can be helped.\" According to the news report, \"She says she would sell her belongings to keep the ministry going.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newschannel5.com/Global/story.asp?S=5409134|title=Part 1: Is it a ministry or just big business?|date=July 1, 2001|website=NewsChannel5.com|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120224230555/http://www.newschannel5.com/Global/story.asp?S=5409134|archive-date=February 24, 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n=== Remnant Fellowship Church ===\nGwen founded the Remnant Fellowship Church in 1999, which at first was a small gathering at the back of the Weigh Down building in Franklin, TN in the shipping department.<ref name=\"auto\"/> In 2002, the Shamblins purchased 40 acres of land in [[Brentwood, Tennessee]], where construction for the church building took place.<ref name=\"auto\"/><ref>{{cite web |title=www.youtube.com |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=HO1FBW2aeNA&list=PLlUntELbdEQK4C0b_onCAJ-RTFnhWuFaM |website=Youtube.com}}</ref>\n\nBuilding of the church wrapped up in 2004.<ref>{{cite web |title=www.youtube.com |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=HO1FBW2aeNA |website=www.Youtube.com}}</ref>\n\nThe church has members from all across the world, including [[Europe]], [[Asia]], [[Africa]], [[North America]], [[South America]], [[Australia]], and [[Canada]]. \n\nThe church does a live webcast for their church program. normally, services are 6:00 PM Wednesdays (CDT) and 9:00 AM Saturday (CDT)<ref>{{cite web |title=remnantfellowship.tv |url=http://www.remnantfellowship.org/rfvisitor.aspx |website=remnantfellowship.tv}}</ref>. The church's membership count is over a thousand.\n\n=== Writings ===\nGwen Shamblin Lara is the author of ''The Weigh Down Diet''.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/217232683|title=Dietitian says God, not food fills void|last=Booth|first=Claire|date=1997-03-14|work=The Times|access-date=2017-07-05|location=[[Shreveport, Louisiana]]|page=2D|language=en}}</ref> First published in March 1997, this diet \u201cadvises using spirituality to avoid [[overeating]] and has sold more than 1.2 million copies.\u201d<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://content.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,33169-3,00.html|title=The Low-Carb Diet Craze|last=Stein|first=Joel|date=1999-10-24|work=Time|access-date=2017-07-05|language=en-US|issn=0040-781X}}</ref> The publisher [[Doubleday (publisher)|Doubleday]] reported selling four hundred thousand copies in less than a year.<ref name=\":8\" /> In this book, Gwen expounds on her theory that there are two very different needs in each person: a need for food and an emotional need. According to her, people should only eat when they feel real, physical hunger and stop when full; prayer and [[Bible]] reading will fill emotional needs instead of food. Overeating is equated with greed. A core principle of The Weigh Down Diet, when people feel an urge to snack but are not experiencing [[Hunger|physiological hunger]], Gwen encourages participants to read the Bible instead.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.usnews.com/usnews/culture/articles/970505/archive_006847.htm|title=A Godly Approach to Weight Loss|last=Mulrine|first=Anna|date=1997-04-27|work=[[U.S. News & World Report]]|archive-url=https://archive.is/20130205070344/http://www.usnews.com/usnews/culture/articles/970505/archive_006847.htm|archive-date=2013-02-05|url-status=dead|accessdate=2007-04-06}}</ref>\n\nSince the release of her first book, Gwen has written a number of books including ''Rise Above''<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/riseabovegodcans00sham|url-access=registration|title=Rise Above: God Can Set You Free from Your Weight Problems Forever|last=Shamblin|first=Gwen|date=2000|publisher=T. Nelson|isbn=9780785268765|location=|pages=|language=en}}</ref> and a [[Self-publishing|self-published]] [[Christian devotional literature|devotional book]] titled ''Exodus''.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=QWmlUkN2ffcC|title=Exodus: Daily Devotional|last=Shamblin|first=Gwen|date=1998-09-01|publisher=Weigh Down Workshop|isbn=9781892729002|language=en}}</ref>\n\nControversy arose when Gwen began to teach that the doctrine of the [[Trinity]] was not Biblical. She stated that she believes Jesus Christ is not God but rather God's son.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.trinitycontroversy.com|title=Home|first=Trinity|last=Controversy|website=www.trinitycontroversy.com|accessdate=20 July 2018}}</ref> This led Thomas Nelson Publishers to cancel the publication of ''Exodus'', her next work. In a letter to her followers sent to clarify her position on the Trinity, Gwen wrote: \"The reason all of this is important is that if you do not understand that God is the clear authority and that Jesus was under God's authority, then you will not have a clear picture of what it means to be Christ like. Jesus suffered, obeyed, submitted, denied his will, and made it his food to do the will of the Father.\" Later she writes, \"I believe that Jesus and God are two separate beings.\" She also says that she does not believe that Jesus and God are equal in power and glory.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://www.christianitytoday.com/ct/2000/septemberweb-only/53.0a.html|title=The Weigh Is Narrow|last=Veenker|first=Jody|date=September 1, 2000|accessdate=2007-04-09|magazine=[[Christianity Today]]}}</ref>\n\n===Television, magazine and news media appearances===\nThe popularity of Gwen's teachings has resulted in its appearances on [[BBC]],<ref name=\"Weigh Down Media\">{{cite web |title= BBC Features Gwen Shamblin and Weigh Down |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=WhiXKYCi5tw |accessdate=29 April 2019}}</ref> [[20/20 (U.S. TV series)|''20/20'']],<ref name=\":9\" />, ''[[A Current Affair (U.S. TV series)|A Current Affair]],<ref name=\":7\" />'', ''[[The View (U.S. TV series)|The View]]'',<ref name=\"watchman Profile\">{{cite web |title=Profile: Weigh Down Workshop/ Remnant Fellowship |url=https://www.watchman.org/profiles/pdf/weighdownprofile.pdf |accessdate=29 April 2019 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161020141838/https://www.watchman.org/profiles/pdf/weighdownprofile.pdf |archivedate=October 20, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"Germantown News\">{{cite news |title=Founder of Weigh Down Workshop to hold seminar at Great Hall |newspaper=Germantown News |date=April 6, 2011 |page=7B |quote=Gwen Shamblin and the Weigh Down Workshop was featured on such shows as 20/20, Larry King Live, and The View, as well as in such magazines as Good Housekeeping and Woman's Day}}</ref> and [[Dateline (Australian TV program)|''Dateline'']] (Australian)<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.sbs.com.au/news/article/2001/03/28/week-dateline-slim-him|title=This week on Dateline: Slim for Him|work=News|access-date=2017-07-08|language=en}}</ref> as well as in such magazines as ''[[Family Circle]]'',<ref name=\":14\" /> ''[[Good Housekeeping]]'',<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.goodhousekeeping.com/health/diet-nutrition/a16666/lose-weight-inspiration-stories/|title=Lose the Weight for Good!|last=Torgovnick|first=Kate|date=2008-01-31|work=Good Housekeeping|access-date=2017-07-08|language=en}}</ref> ''[[Woman's Day]]'',<ref name=\":22\" /> and many newspaper articles.<ref name=\":10\" /><ref name=\":122\" /><ref name=\":132\" /> She has been featured on ''[[Today (U.S. TV program)|The Today Show]]'',<ref name=\"Today Show\">{{cite web |title=The Today Show's Matt Lauer Interviews Gwen Shamblin Weigh Down Founder |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=DD45ICXtwhk |accessdate=29 April 2019}}</ref> [[CNN]]'s ''[[Larry King Live]]'',''<ref name=\":7\" /><ref name=\":9\" />'' ''[[DaySide]]'',<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.foxnews.com/video2/launchPage.html?082306/082306_ds_faith&Faith-Based%20Diet%3F&DaySide&Can%20praying%20help%20you%20lose%20weight%3F&Health&-1&Faith-Based%20Diet%3F&Video%20Launch%20Page&News|title=Can Praying Help You Lose Weight?|date=2004-06-14|publisher=[[Fox News]]|accessdate=}}</ref> and ''[[The Early Show]]''.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cbsnews.com/sections/earlyshow/main500202.shtml|title=The Early Show|publisher=[[CBS]]|accessdate=}}</ref> Participants from the Weigh Down Workshop have been featured on the cover of ''[[Good Housekeeping]]'',<ref>{{Cite news|url=|title=Slim-Down Secrets|last=Bollinger|first=Caroline|date=April 2007|work=Good House Keeping|access-date=|pages=158\u2013160}}</ref> in the ''[[Ladies' Home Journal]]'',<ref>{{Cite news|url=|title=Diet help from on high?|last=Cherry|first=Rona|date=January 2007|work=Ladies' Home Journal|access-date=}}</ref> in ''[[People (magazine)|People Magazine]]'',<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://people.com/archive/incredible-shrinking-couple-vol-69-no-1/|title=Incredible Shrinking Couple|last=Williams|first=Ashley|date=2008-01-14|work=People Magazine|access-date=2017-07-08|issue=1|volume=69|language=en-US}}</ref> ''First'' magazine,<ref>{{Cite news|url=|title=I stopped thinking about food and the fat fell off!|last=|first=|date=2005-04-11|work=First Magazine|access-date=}}</ref> ''Quick and Simple'',<ref>{{Cite news|url=|title=How I Prayed Off the Pounds|last=|first=|date=2007-05-29|work=Quick & Simple|access-date=|pages=8\u20139}}</ref> and in numerous newspaper articles. In 2007, ''[[The Tyra Banks Show]]'' devoted an hour-long program to Gwen, the Weigh Down Diet,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.tvguide.com/tvshows/the-tyra-show/episode-143-season-2/church-of-thin/195018/|title=The Tyra Show: Season 2, Episode 143 Church of Thin|last=|first=|date=2007-05-10|website=TV Guide|language=en|access-date=2017-07-08}}</ref> the Fellowship and participants from Weigh Down programs.\n\nIn 2009, Gwen and Weigh Down were featured on such television programs as [[We TV (U.S. TV channel)|WeTV]]'s ''[[Secret Lives of Women]]'',<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wetv.com/videos/extreme-diets-gods-diet|title=Extreme Diets: God's Diet|website=WE tv|language=en-US|access-date=2017-07-08}}</ref> [[CBS]]\u2019s ''[[The Insider (TV series)|The Insider]].{{Citation needed|date=July 2017}}'' In late 2011, She began producing a live Internet show, titled ''You Can Overcome''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.remnantfellowship.tv/you-can-overcome/|title=You Can Overcome Show Archives - Remnant Fellowship TV|website=Remnant Fellowship TV|language=en-US|access-date=2017-07-08}}</ref>\n\n==Selected works==\n\n===Books===\n* {{Cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/weighdowndiet00sham|url-access=registration|title=The Weigh Down Diet|date=1997|publisher=Doubleday|isbn=9780385487627|language=en}}\n\n* {{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=QWmlUkN2ffcC|title=Exodus: Daily Devotional|date=1998|publisher=Weigh Down Workshop|isbn=9781892729002|location=|pages=|language=en}}\n\n* {{Cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/riseabovegodcans00sham|url-access=registration|title=Rise Above: God Can Set You Free from Your Weight Problems Forever|date=2000|publisher=Thomas Nelson|isbn=9780785268765|language=en}}\n* {{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=y5_JkQEACAAJ|title=Out of Egypt: Inspiration for Conquering Life's Strongholds|last=|first=|date=2000|publisher=Thomas Nelson|isbn=9780785268499|location=|pages=|language=en}}\n* {{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=SVUcPQAACAAJ|title=The Legend to the Treasure|date=2007|publisher=Weigh Down Workshop|isbn=9781892729804|language=en}}\n* {{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=y8SQmwEACAAJ|title=Weigh Down Basics: Workbook|date=2012|publisher=Weigh Down Workshop|isbn=9781892729132|language=en}}\n* {{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=M0x8kgEACAAJ|title=History of the One True God Workbook: Volume 1: the Origin of Good and Evil|date=2013|publisher=Weigh Down Workshop|isbn=9781892729170|language=en}}\n* {{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=zehAjgEACAAJ|title=History of the Love of God: Volume II: A Love More Ancient Than Time|date=2015|publisher=Weigh Down Ministries|isbn=9781892729262 |language=en}}\n\n===Other media===\n* {{Citation|title=Exodus out of Egypt: weigh down workshop|date=1992|publisher=Weigh Down Workshop|language=English|oclc=42869110}} \n* {{Citation|title=Rising above: the magnetic pull of the refrigerator|date=1992|publisher=Weigh Down Workshop, Inc.|language=English|oclc=42414509}} \n* {{Citation|title=Exodus from strongholds|date=1998|publisher=Weigh Down Workshop|language=English|isbn=1892729075|oclc=51290468}} \n* {{Citation|title=Weigh down at home|date=1999|publisher=Weigh Down Workshop|language=English|oclc=843098377}} \n*\n*\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|http://www.gwenshamblinlara.com/}}\n* [http://www.remnantfellowship.org Remnant Fellowship Church Website] link retrieved 11/01/2018\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Shamblin Lara, Gwen}}\n[[Category:American non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:Christian writers]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1955 births]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox writer <!-- for more information see [[:Template:Infobox writer/doc]] -->\n| name = Gwen Shamblin Lara\n| image = Gwen Shamblin 2018 (cropped).jpg\n| image_size = \n| caption = \n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|mf=yes|1955|02|18}}\n| birth_place = [[Memphis, Tennessee]], U.S.\n| occupation = Author and Registered Dietician\n| residence = [[Brentwood, Tennessee]]\n| spouse = {{marriage|David Shamblin|1978|2018|reason=divorced}}<br>{{marriage|[[Joe Lara]]|2018}}\n| children = Michael Shamblin,<ref>{{cite web |title=www.michaelshamblin.com |url=http://www.michaelshamblin.com/about/ |website=michaelshamblin.com}}</ref> Elizabeth Shamblin Hannah<ref>{{cite web |title=gwenshamblinbooks.com |url=http://gwenshamblinbooks.com/bio/ |website=gwenshamblinbooks.com}}</ref>\n| genre = [[Self-help]], [[Non-fiction]]\n| movement = \n| influences = \n| influenced = \n| website = {{URL|http://www.gwenshamblin.com/}}\n}}\n'''Gwen Shamblin Lara''' is an American non-fiction author and founder of ''The Weigh Down Workshop'' and founder of the Remnant Fellowship Church. The most distinctive aspect of her writing is its combination of weight loss programs with [[Christianity]].\n\n==Early life==\nGwen earned an [[undergraduate degree]] in [[Dietitian|dietetics]] from [[University of Tennessee]], in [[Knoxville, Tennessee|Knoxville]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://lib.williamson-tn.org/Local_Authors/S.htm#_Shamblin,_Gwen|title=Williamson County Local Authors|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060131093440/http://lib.williamson-tn.org/Local_Authors/S.htm#_Shamblin,_Gwen|archive-date=2006-01-31|url-status=dead|accessdate=2007-04-25|work=Williamson County Library}}</ref> and then her master's degree in food and nutrition<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=|title=Frazee woman shares personal weight loss story|last=Thorp|first=Lori Frazer|date=1998-01-08|work=Frazee Forum|access-date=}}</ref> from the [[University of Memphis|Memphis State University]]. She is a [[Dietitian|registered dietitian]],<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/203907872/|title=Unorthodox diet plan targeted at teens|last=Gang|first=Christine Arpe|date=1988-04-13|work=Longview News-Journal|access-date=2017-07-05|page=4C|language=en}}</ref> consultant, and was a faculty member at the Memphis State University for five years.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|url=|title=Heart & Soul: An interview with Gwen Shamblin, founder of the Weigh Down Workshop|last=|first=|date=February 1999|work=Murfreesboro Matters|access-date=|issue=3|volume=1|page=3}}</ref> She also worked in the [[Tennessee Department of Health|state's health department]]<ref name=\":0\" /> for an additional five years.\n\n==Personal life==\nGwen was raised in a [[Church of Christ]] family.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Kennedy |first1=John W |title=Thomas Nelson pulls plug on Gwen Shamblin's book |url=http://www.bpnews.net/6481/thomas-nelson-pulls-plug-on-gwen-shamblins-book |accessdate=22 July 2019 |date=September 11, 2000}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/136209218/|title=Dieting religiously|last=White|first=Gaule|date=1997-03-31|work=Democrat and Chronicle|access-date=2017-07-05|page=3C|language=en}}</ref> She has two children and seven grandchildren.<ref name=\":7\">{{Cite news|url=|title=Women of the Year: Gwen Shamblin|last=Ieron|first=Julie-Allyson|date=January 2000|work=Clarity Magazine|access-date=}}</ref><ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web |title=remnantfellowship.org |url=http://www.remnantfellowship.org/Our-Leaders/Gwen-Shamblin |website=www.remnantfellowship.org}}</ref>and as of March 1996, Gwen lived with her family in Ashlawn, a historic mansion in [[Brentwood, Tennessee]], that was built in 1838.<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/113496856/|title=You could've had it, for $2.3 million|last=McCampbell|first=Candy|date=1996-03-11|work=The Tennessean|access-date=2017-07-05|page=1E|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.brentwood-tn.org/Modules/ShowDocument.aspx?documentid=417|title=Ashlawn|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100621073800/http://brentwood-tn.org/Modules/ShowDocument.aspx?documentid=417|archive-date=2010-06-21|url-status=dead|accessdate=2011-08-11|work=City of Brentwood}}</ref> In 2018 she married [[Joe Lara]]<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.gwenshamblin.com/about/|title=About - Gwen Shamblin|work=Gwen Shamblin|access-date=2018-08-28|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n== Ministry career ==\n\n===Weigh Down Workshop===\nGwen began her consulting practice in the area of weight control in 1980.<ref name=\":1\" /> She had struggled with her weight while attending school.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/local/1997/05/17/dieters-putting-their-faith-in-sustenance-of-the-spirit/d514bacc-c4b8-4eb9-a7fa-568354a44f68/|title=Dieters putting their faith in sustenance of the spirit|last=Hull|first=Dana|date=1997-05-17|work=The Washington Post|access-date=2017-07-05|language=en-US|issn=0190-8286}}</ref> She became \"convinced that [[genetics]], [[metabolism]] and [[behavior modification]] alone couldn't explain why some people were thin and others battled the bulge.\"<ref name=\":22\">{{cite news|url=|title=Divine Intervention|last=Spencer|first=Paula|date=1994-11-22|work=[[Woman's Day]]|access-date=|pages=76, 78}}</ref> In 1986, Gwen founded the Weigh Down Workshop,<ref name=\":32\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/112566660/|title=Churchgoers leaning on God to shed their unwanted pounds|last=Waddle|first=Ray|date=1994-02-27|work=The Tennessean|access-date=2017-07-05|page=2A|language=en}}</ref><ref name=\":42\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/113393691/|title=Weigh Down transfers love for food into love for God|last=Waddle|first=Ray|date=1996-07-03|work=The Tennessean|access-date=2017-07-05|pages=1B\u20132B|language=en}}</ref> a [[Dieting|weight loss program]] which has \u201cno forbidden foods, exercise regimen or weigh-ins,\u201d<ref name=\":52\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/205898521/|title=God is focus of weight-loss program|last=Associated Press|first=|date=1995-01-03|work=Battle Creek Enquirer|access-date=2017-07-05|page=4A|language=en}}</ref> and avoids \u201c[[A calorie is a calorie#Calorie counting|calorie counting]].\u201d<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/159455908/|title=The Weigh to the Lite|last=Whyche|first=Stephanie|date=1995-10-09|work=The News Journal|access-date=2017-07-05|pages=C1, C4|language=en}}</ref> As ''[[The Tennessean]]'' points out, the program lacks \u201csome basic elements,\u201d like exercise and guidance on food selection, as recommended by the [[Academy of Nutrition and Dietetics|American Dietetic Association]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/112841589/|title=Praying away the pounds|last=Quigley|first=Linda|date=1997-03-01|work=The Tennessean|access-date=2017-07-05|pages=1D, 4D|language=en}}</ref> According to ''[[The Philadelphia Inquirer]]'', \u201cthe Weigh Down Workshop attempts to help participants develop the discipline to eat only when they are hungry and to stop eating when they are full.\u201d<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/178355816/|title=Christian dieters saying faith can defeat fat|last=Holmes|first=Kristin E.|date=1996-05-06|work=The Philadelphia Inquirer|access-date=2017-07-05|pages=B1, B3|language=en}}</ref>\n\nGwen developed the program while working on her master's degree at Memphis State University.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/222544335/|title=Program helps dieters succeed|last=Kleczynski|first=Jennifer Coleridge|date=1995-04-21|work=Strictly Hunterdon|access-date=2017-07-05|publisher=The Courier-News|page=5|language=en}}</ref> As part of a counseling center,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/159376638/|title=Dieters seek help in religion|last=|first=|date=1997-04-13|work=The News Journal|access-date=2017-07-05|pages=J1, J7|language=en}}</ref> she held the first class in a mall in Memphis, Tennessee;<ref name=\":10\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/archives/nydn-features/wages-thin-putting-grace-meals-christian-diet-programs-reshaping-lives-article-1.792223|title=The wages of thin: By putting grace before meals, Christian diet programs are reshaping lives|last=Bell|first=Bill|date=1998-06-17|work=New York Daily News|access-date=2017-07-05|language=en}}</ref> the program was initially only offered as small classes in similar retail<ref name=\":11\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/138503800/|title=Weight-loss disciples are shedding the extra pounds through prayer|last=Graham|first=Jennifer|date=1994-12-07|work=Democrat and Chronicle|access-date=2017-07-05|pages=1C, 6C|language=en}}</ref> and other non-religious settings.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/77357120/|title=Weighty matters|last=Wells|first=Valerie|date=1995-05-06|work=Herald and Review|access-date=2017-07-05|language=en}}</ref> In 1991<ref name=\":32\" /><ref name=\":42\" /> or 1992, she began hosting the program at [[Bellevue Baptist Church]] located in the Memphis area.<ref name=\":8\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/113428692|title=In God's own image|last=Hill|first=Laura|date=1998-02-10|work=The Tennessean|access-date=2017-07-05|language=en}}</ref> The program consists of twelve-week seminars guided by video and audio tapes featuring Gwen.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.greensboro.com/faith-helps-some-people-lower-weight-way-down/article_e2d14ec6-826c-5669-abfa-fb62ec1e134b.html|title=Faith helps some people lower weight way down|last=Johnson II|first=Lucas L.|date=1996-07-18|work=Greensboro News & Record|access-date=2017-07-05|agency=The Associated Press|language=en}}</ref> The meetings consist of a group viewing of one of her videos, along with prayer and discussion.<ref name=\":122\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/lifestyle/1995/01/23/dieting-with-jesus/67735e60-9238-4b4c-9ea2-ae3391d2b677/|title=Dieting with Jesus|last=Rosenfeld|first=Megan|date=1995-01-23|work=The Washington Post|access-date=2017-07-05|language=en-US}}</ref> By 1994, the program quickly spread as far away as Europe and was offered in about 600 churches in at least 35 US States.<ref name=\":22\" />\n\nAccording to the [[Associated Press]], by January 1995, the program could be found in over 1,000 churches in forty-nine US States, as well as at locations in Britain and Canada;<ref name=\":52\" /> but by July 1996, the workshop was at about 5,000 churches, with close to ten percent located in Gwen's home-state of Tennessee.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/285568028|title=Program urges people to turn to God to shed pounds|last=Associated Press|first=|date=1996-07-26|work=The Daily Spectrum|access-date=2017-07-05|language=en}}</ref> As many as eight churches in Britain were hosting workshops by December 1996.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/258291780/|title=The divine diet|last=Brooks|first=Richard|date=1996-12-29|work=The Observer|access-date=2017-07-05|language=en}}</ref> Some participants in the US would also host meetings in their private homes.<ref name=\":32\" />\n\nIn 1996, Weigh Down, which consisted of a forty-person staff, began building a headquarters in [[Franklin, Tennessee]].<ref name=\":42\" /> The same year, Gwen Shamblin Lara and Weigh Down began hosting an annual summer convention, known as Desert Oasis, in the [[Nashville, Tennessee|Nashville]] area.<ref name=\":42\" /><ref name=\":9\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/205068421|title=Heavenly help|last=De La Cruz|first=Jessi|date=1999-03-19|work=Lansing State Journal|access-date=2017-07-05|language=en}}</ref>\n\nBy August 1998, Weigh Down was holding more than 21,000 classes with over 250,000 reported participants worldwide.<ref name=\":132\">{{Cite news|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1998-08-20/features/9808200388_1_gwen-shamblin-weigh-smaller-sizes|title=Christian Diet Programs: Nourishing The Spirit Is The Key To Slimming Down The Body|last=Lauerman|first=Connie|date=1998-08-20|work=Chicago Tribune|access-date=2017-07-05|language=en}}</ref> Weigh Down Workshop classes would eventually spread to all fifty US states<ref name=\":42\" /> and every continent,<ref name=\"Random House2\">{{cite web|url=http://www.randomhouse.com/author/results.pperl?authorid=27826|title=Random House|accessdate=2010-02-11}}</ref> becoming \"one of the most popular weight-loss programs in the world\" by mid-2000.<ref name=\":14\">{{cite news|url=|title=The Power to Change|last=Long|first=Marion|date=May 2000|work=Family Circle|access-date=|pages=58\u201359}}</ref> Gwen has also been traveling to other cities as part of the ''Rebuilding the Wall'' tour.<ref name=\":15\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.christianitytoday.com/ct/2002/december9/6.15.html|title=New Sect: Weigh Down guru Gwen Shamblin's Remnant Fellowship grows.|last=Kennedy|first=John W.|date=2002-12-09|work=Christianity Today|access-date=2017-07-05|language=en}}</ref>\n\nOther dietitians have questioned the soundness of Gwen's diet advice, which focuses on faith instead of healthy eating habits or exercise.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.redorbit.com/news/health/470079/god_is_their_weightloss_guru/index.html|title=God is Their Weight-Loss Guru|last=Morning News|first=Dallas|date=2006-04-14|accessdate=2007-04-09|newspaper=[[The Dallas Morning News]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.skinnyondiets.com/GwenShamblinsWeighDownWorkshop.html?b=8277&GCID=S15771x274&KEYWORD=gwen%20shamblin&gclid=CLK6suekgYwCFR05UQodDiLcwQ|title=Gwen Shamblin's Weigh Down Workshop|publisher=skinnyondiets.com|accessdate=2007-05-23|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070927075755/http://www.skinnyondiets.com/GwenShamblinsWeighDownWorkshop.html?b=8277&GCID=S15771x274&KEYWORD=gwen%20shamblin&gclid=CLK6suekgYwCFR05UQodDiLcwQ|archive-date=2007-09-27|url-status=dead}}</ref> In the book ''Born Again Bodies: Flesh and Spirit in American Christianity'', author Marie Griffith, a [[Princeton University]] associate professor of religion, examines the trend of religion-based dieting. Although critical of Gwen for using the Christianity label while building her business, Griffith credits her for the new wave of interest in creating \"a more holy body\", and substantial sections of the work examine Shamblin's movement.<ref name=\"griffith2004\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=dGtHZImY4lcC|title=Born Again Bodies: Flesh and Spirit in American Christianity|last=Griffith|first=R. Marie|date=2004-10-04|publisher=University of California Press|isbn=9780520938113|language=en}}</ref> Griffith notes, \"In Shamblin's world, people who don't lose weight often feel like failures. If they don't lose weight, it's a failure of discipline; it's a failure of obedience.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.princeton.edu/news/2005/01/27/religion-professor-examines-salvation-diet-phenomenon|title=Religion professor examines 'salvation by diet' phenomenon|last=Allen|first=Patricia|date=2005-01-27|work=News@Princeton|accessdate=2007-05-23|publisher=|pages=}}</ref> At the same time, Griffith's work places Shamblin's movement squarely within a historical tradition of perfecting one's body in order to be more [[Jesus|Christ]]-like, or fasting and dieting in order to feel closer to God.<ref name=\"griffith2004\" />\n\nIn 2001, NewsChannel 5, a local Nashville news station, aired a story entitled \"Is it a ministry or just big business?\", looking into how Weigh Down Workshop's money was spent. Towards the end of the interview, Gwen states that \"half of [the money] goes to the government, the other half goes to keep it going so someone else can be helped.\" According to the news report, \"She says she would sell her belongings to keep the ministry going.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newschannel5.com/Global/story.asp?S=5409134|title=Part 1: Is it a ministry or just big business?|date=July 1, 2001|website=NewsChannel5.com|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120224230555/http://www.newschannel5.com/Global/story.asp?S=5409134|archive-date=February 24, 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n=== Remnant Fellowship Church ===\nGwen founded the Remnant Fellowship Church in 1999, which at first was a small gathering at the back of the Weigh Down building in Franklin, TN in the shipping department.<ref name=\"auto\"/> In 2002, the Shamblins purchased 40 acres of land in [[Brentwood, Tennessee]], where construction for the church building took place.<ref name=\"auto\"/><ref>{{cite web |title=www.youtube.com |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=HO1FBW2aeNA&list=PLlUntELbdEQK4C0b_onCAJ-RTFnhWuFaM |website=Youtube.com}}</ref>\n\nBuilding of the church wrapped up in 2004.<ref>{{cite web |title=www.youtube.com |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=HO1FBW2aeNA |website=www.Youtube.com}}</ref>\n\nThe church has members from all across the world, including [[Europe]], [[Asia]], [[Africa]], [[North America]], [[South America]], [[Australia]], and [[Canada]]. \n\nThe church does a live webcast for their church program. normally, services are 6:00 PM Wednesdays (CDT) and 9:00 AM Saturday (CDT)<ref>{{cite web |title=remnantfellowship.tv |url=http://www.remnantfellowship.org/rfvisitor.aspx |website=remnantfellowship.tv}}</ref>. The church's membership count is over a thousand.\n\nThe church has been labeled as a cult that practices cult like mind control on its members. They believe that criticizing or disagreeing with Gwen Shamblin is out of the will of God where she sets herself up as a prophet of God.<ref>{{cite web |title=What is the Remnant Fellowship? |url=https://www.gotquestions.org/Remnant-Fellowship.html |website=Got Questions}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Remnant Fellowship: A Brief History And A Dire Warning |url=http://spiritwatch.org/remnantwatch.htm |website=Spiritwatch Ministries}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Remnant Fellowship |url=https://www.allaboutcults.org/remnant-fellowship.htm |website=All About Cults}}</ref><ref name=\"NBC News\">{{cite news |title=Church stands by parents convicted of death |url=http://www.nbcnews.com/id/17842789/ns/us_news-crime_and_courts/t/church-stands-parents-convicted-death/#.XjlYA2hKgqg |accessdate=4 February 2020 |date=March 29, 2007}}</ref>\n\n=== Writings ===\nGwen Shamblin Lara is the author of ''The Weigh Down Diet''.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/217232683|title=Dietitian says God, not food fills void|last=Booth|first=Claire|date=1997-03-14|work=The Times|access-date=2017-07-05|location=[[Shreveport, Louisiana]]|page=2D|language=en}}</ref> First published in March 1997, this diet \u201cadvises using spirituality to avoid [[overeating]] and has sold more than 1.2 million copies.\u201d<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://content.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,33169-3,00.html|title=The Low-Carb Diet Craze|last=Stein|first=Joel|date=1999-10-24|work=Time|access-date=2017-07-05|language=en-US|issn=0040-781X}}</ref> The publisher [[Doubleday (publisher)|Doubleday]] reported selling four hundred thousand copies in less than a year.<ref name=\":8\" /> In this book, Gwen expounds on her theory that there are two very different needs in each person: a need for food and an emotional need. According to her, people should only eat when they feel real, physical hunger and stop when full; prayer and [[Bible]] reading will fill emotional needs instead of food. Overeating is equated with greed. A core principle of The Weigh Down Diet, when people feel an urge to snack but are not experiencing [[Hunger|physiological hunger]], Gwen encourages participants to read the Bible instead.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.usnews.com/usnews/culture/articles/970505/archive_006847.htm|title=A Godly Approach to Weight Loss|last=Mulrine|first=Anna|date=1997-04-27|work=[[U.S. News & World Report]]|archive-url=https://archive.is/20130205070344/http://www.usnews.com/usnews/culture/articles/970505/archive_006847.htm|archive-date=2013-02-05|url-status=dead|accessdate=2007-04-06}}</ref>\n\nSince the release of her first book, Gwen has written a number of books including ''Rise Above''<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/riseabovegodcans00sham|url-access=registration|title=Rise Above: God Can Set You Free from Your Weight Problems Forever|last=Shamblin|first=Gwen|date=2000|publisher=T. Nelson|isbn=9780785268765|location=|pages=|language=en}}</ref> and a [[Self-publishing|self-published]] [[Christian devotional literature|devotional book]] titled ''Exodus''.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=QWmlUkN2ffcC|title=Exodus: Daily Devotional|last=Shamblin|first=Gwen|date=1998-09-01|publisher=Weigh Down Workshop|isbn=9781892729002|language=en}}</ref>\n\nControversy arose when Gwen began to teach that the doctrine of the [[Trinity]] was not Biblical. She stated that she believes Jesus Christ is not God but rather God's son.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.trinitycontroversy.com|title=Home|first=Trinity|last=Controversy|website=www.trinitycontroversy.com|accessdate=20 July 2018}}</ref> This led Thomas Nelson Publishers to cancel the publication of ''Exodus'', her next work. In a letter to her followers sent to clarify her position on the Trinity, Gwen wrote: \"The reason all of this is important is that if you do not understand that God is the clear authority and that Jesus was under God's authority, then you will not have a clear picture of what it means to be Christ like. Jesus suffered, obeyed, submitted, denied his will, and made it his food to do the will of the Father.\" Later she writes, \"I believe that Jesus and God are two separate beings.\" She also says that she does not believe that Jesus and God are equal in power and glory.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://www.christianitytoday.com/ct/2000/septemberweb-only/53.0a.html|title=The Weigh Is Narrow|last=Veenker|first=Jody|date=September 1, 2000|accessdate=2007-04-09|magazine=[[Christianity Today]]}}</ref>\n\n===Television, magazine and news media appearances===\nThe popularity of Gwen's teachings has resulted in its appearances on [[BBC]],<ref name=\"Weigh Down Media\">{{cite web |title= BBC Features Gwen Shamblin and Weigh Down |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=WhiXKYCi5tw |accessdate=29 April 2019}}</ref> [[20/20 (U.S. TV series)|''20/20'']],<ref name=\":9\" />, ''[[A Current Affair (U.S. TV series)|A Current Affair]],<ref name=\":7\" />'', ''[[The View (U.S. TV series)|The View]]'',<ref name=\"watchman Profile\">{{cite web |title=Profile: Weigh Down Workshop/ Remnant Fellowship |url=https://www.watchman.org/profiles/pdf/weighdownprofile.pdf |accessdate=29 April 2019 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161020141838/https://www.watchman.org/profiles/pdf/weighdownprofile.pdf |archivedate=October 20, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"Germantown News\">{{cite news |title=Founder of Weigh Down Workshop to hold seminar at Great Hall |newspaper=Germantown News |date=April 6, 2011 |page=7B |quote=Gwen Shamblin and the Weigh Down Workshop was featured on such shows as 20/20, Larry King Live, and The View, as well as in such magazines as Good Housekeeping and Woman's Day}}</ref> and [[Dateline (Australian TV program)|''Dateline'']] (Australian)<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.sbs.com.au/news/article/2001/03/28/week-dateline-slim-him|title=This week on Dateline: Slim for Him|work=News|access-date=2017-07-08|language=en}}</ref> as well as in such magazines as ''[[Family Circle]]'',<ref name=\":14\" /> ''[[Good Housekeeping]]'',<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.goodhousekeeping.com/health/diet-nutrition/a16666/lose-weight-inspiration-stories/|title=Lose the Weight for Good!|last=Torgovnick|first=Kate|date=2008-01-31|work=Good Housekeeping|access-date=2017-07-08|language=en}}</ref> ''[[Woman's Day]]'',<ref name=\":22\" /> and many newspaper articles.<ref name=\":10\" /><ref name=\":122\" /><ref name=\":132\" /> She has been featured on ''[[Today (U.S. TV program)|The Today Show]]'',<ref name=\"Today Show\">{{cite web |title=The Today Show's Matt Lauer Interviews Gwen Shamblin Weigh Down Founder |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=DD45ICXtwhk |accessdate=29 April 2019}}</ref> [[CNN]]'s ''[[Larry King Live]]'',''<ref name=\":7\" /><ref name=\":9\" />'' ''[[DaySide]]'',<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.foxnews.com/video2/launchPage.html?082306/082306_ds_faith&Faith-Based%20Diet%3F&DaySide&Can%20praying%20help%20you%20lose%20weight%3F&Health&-1&Faith-Based%20Diet%3F&Video%20Launch%20Page&News|title=Can Praying Help You Lose Weight?|date=2004-06-14|publisher=[[Fox News]]|accessdate=}}</ref> and ''[[The Early Show]]''.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cbsnews.com/sections/earlyshow/main500202.shtml|title=The Early Show|publisher=[[CBS]]|accessdate=}}</ref> Participants from the Weigh Down Workshop have been featured on the cover of ''[[Good Housekeeping]]'',<ref>{{Cite news|url=|title=Slim-Down Secrets|last=Bollinger|first=Caroline|date=April 2007|work=Good House Keeping|access-date=|pages=158\u2013160}}</ref> in the ''[[Ladies' Home Journal]]'',<ref>{{Cite news|url=|title=Diet help from on high?|last=Cherry|first=Rona|date=January 2007|work=Ladies' Home Journal|access-date=}}</ref> in ''[[People (magazine)|People Magazine]]'',<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://people.com/archive/incredible-shrinking-couple-vol-69-no-1/|title=Incredible Shrinking Couple|last=Williams|first=Ashley|date=2008-01-14|work=People Magazine|access-date=2017-07-08|issue=1|volume=69|language=en-US}}</ref> ''First'' magazine,<ref>{{Cite news|url=|title=I stopped thinking about food and the fat fell off!|last=|first=|date=2005-04-11|work=First Magazine|access-date=}}</ref> ''Quick and Simple'',<ref>{{Cite news|url=|title=How I Prayed Off the Pounds|last=|first=|date=2007-05-29|work=Quick & Simple|access-date=|pages=8\u20139}}</ref> and in numerous newspaper articles. In 2007, ''[[The Tyra Banks Show]]'' devoted an hour-long program to Gwen, the Weigh Down Diet,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.tvguide.com/tvshows/the-tyra-show/episode-143-season-2/church-of-thin/195018/|title=The Tyra Show: Season 2, Episode 143 Church of Thin|last=|first=|date=2007-05-10|website=TV Guide|language=en|access-date=2017-07-08}}</ref> the Fellowship and participants from Weigh Down programs.\n\nIn 2009, Gwen and Weigh Down were featured on such television programs as [[We TV (U.S. TV channel)|WeTV]]'s ''[[Secret Lives of Women]]'',<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wetv.com/videos/extreme-diets-gods-diet|title=Extreme Diets: God's Diet|website=WE tv|language=en-US|access-date=2017-07-08}}</ref> [[CBS]]\u2019s ''[[The Insider (TV series)|The Insider]].{{Citation needed|date=July 2017}}'' In late 2011, She began producing a live Internet show, titled ''You Can Overcome''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.remnantfellowship.tv/you-can-overcome/|title=You Can Overcome Show Archives - Remnant Fellowship TV|website=Remnant Fellowship TV|language=en-US|access-date=2017-07-08}}</ref>\n\n==Selected works==\n\n===Books===\n* {{Cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/weighdowndiet00sham|url-access=registration|title=The Weigh Down Diet|date=1997|publisher=Doubleday|isbn=9780385487627|language=en}}\n\n* {{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=QWmlUkN2ffcC|title=Exodus: Daily Devotional|date=1998|publisher=Weigh Down Workshop|isbn=9781892729002|location=|pages=|language=en}}\n\n* {{Cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/riseabovegodcans00sham|url-access=registration|title=Rise Above: God Can Set You Free from Your Weight Problems Forever|date=2000|publisher=Thomas Nelson|isbn=9780785268765|language=en}}\n* {{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=y5_JkQEACAAJ|title=Out of Egypt: Inspiration for Conquering Life's Strongholds|last=|first=|date=2000|publisher=Thomas Nelson|isbn=9780785268499|location=|pages=|language=en}}\n* {{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=SVUcPQAACAAJ|title=The Legend to the Treasure|date=2007|publisher=Weigh Down Workshop|isbn=9781892729804|language=en}}\n* {{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=y8SQmwEACAAJ|title=Weigh Down Basics: Workbook|date=2012|publisher=Weigh Down Workshop|isbn=9781892729132|language=en}}\n* {{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=M0x8kgEACAAJ|title=History of the One True God Workbook: Volume 1: the Origin of Good and Evil|date=2013|publisher=Weigh Down Workshop|isbn=9781892729170|language=en}}\n* {{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=zehAjgEACAAJ|title=History of the Love of God: Volume II: A Love More Ancient Than Time|date=2015|publisher=Weigh Down Ministries|isbn=9781892729262 |language=en}}\n\n===Other media===\n* {{Citation|title=Exodus out of Egypt: weigh down workshop|date=1992|publisher=Weigh Down Workshop|language=English|oclc=42869110}} \n* {{Citation|title=Rising above: the magnetic pull of the refrigerator|date=1992|publisher=Weigh Down Workshop, Inc.|language=English|oclc=42414509}} \n* {{Citation|title=Exodus from strongholds|da